Functions to select the pictures with best valence.

select.best <- function(val, lab, n.x = 15) {
  # selectionne les pictures avec les 15 plus hautes valences
  #          et les pictures avec les 15 plus basses valences
  
  attraction <- vector(mode = "character", length(lab))
  
  x <- data.frame(Label = lab,
                  Valence = val) %>%
    group_by(Label) %>%
    summarise(Valence = unique(Valence))
  
  lab.neutre  <- x$Label[order(x$Valence, decreasing = FALSE)[1:n.x]]
  lab.attract <- x$Label[order(x$Valence, decreasing = TRUE)[1:n.x]]

  attraction[lab %in% lab.neutre]  <- "Neutre"
  attraction[lab %in% lab.attract] <- "Attract"
  return(attraction)
}

FAB compute

Functions to compute FAB.
\(FAB = (RT^{Avoid}_{Attract} - RT^{Appro}_{Attract}) - (RT^{Avoid}_{Neutre} - RT^{Appro}_{Neutre})\)

FAB <- function(RT, Zoom, Attraction){
  
  x = data.frame(RT         = RT,
                 Zoom       = Zoom,
                 Attraction = Attraction)
  
  Avoid.Attract <- x %>%
    filter(Zoom == "out", Attraction == "Attract") %>%
    dplyr::select(RT)
  Avoid.Neutre <- x %>%
    filter(Zoom == "out", Attraction == "Neutre") %>%
    dplyr::select(RT)
  Appro.Attract <- x %>%
    filter(Zoom == "in", Attraction == "Attract") %>%
    dplyr::select(RT)
  Appro.Neutre <- x %>%
    filter(Zoom == "in", Attraction == "Neutre") %>%
    dplyr::select(RT)
  
  FAB.score = (mean(Avoid.Attract$RT, na.rm = TRUE)-mean(Appro.Attract$RT, na.rm = TRUE))-(mean(Avoid.Neutre$RT, na.rm = TRUE) - mean(Appro.Neutre$RT, na.rm = TRUE))
  
  
  return(list(FAB.score = FAB.score,
       Avoid.Attract = mean(Avoid.Attract$RT, na.rm = TRUE),
       Avoid.Neutre = mean(Avoid.Neutre$RT, na.rm = TRUE),
       Appro.Attract = mean(Appro.Attract$RT, na.rm = TRUE),
       Appro.Neutre = mean(Appro.Neutre$RT, na.rm = TRUE)))

}
donne <- donne %>%
  group_by(Sujet) %>%
  mutate(Attraction = select.best(Valence_Suj, Label_Pict, 15)) %>%
  filter(Attraction != "") %>%
  group_by(Sujet, Bloc) %>%
  mutate(FAB           = FAB(RT, Zoom, Attraction)$FAB.score,
         Avoid.Attract = FAB(RT, Zoom, Attraction)$Avoid.Attract,
         Avoid.Neutre  = FAB(RT, Zoom, Attraction)$Avoid.Neutre,
         Appro.Attract = FAB(RT, Zoom, Attraction)$Appro.Attract,
         Appro.Neutre  = FAB(RT, Zoom, Attraction)$Appro.Neutre) %>%
  dplyr::select(-Smoking, -Canabis, -Alcohol, -Zoom, -RT, -Valence_Theo, -Valence_Suj, -Label_Pict, -Attraction)

Delta compute

I compute the delta between states and Control condition. So :
- Value_delta = Value_Meditation - Value_Control

donne %>%
  dplyr::select(Sujet, Bloc, states,
                difficulty, emotion, absorp, meta, realness,
                FAB, Avoid.Attract, Avoid.Neutre, Appro.Attract, Appro.Neutre,
                Stabilo_20, Stabilo_40, Stabilo_1500, Stabilo_3000, Stabilo_error, Stabilo_mean, Stabilo_med) %>%
  unique() %>%
  filter(Bloc == 1) %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::select(-Bloc, -states) %>%
  dplyr::rename(Ctrl_difficulty = difficulty,
                Ctrl_emotion = emotion,
                Ctrl_absorp = absorp,
                Ctrl_meta = meta,
                Ctrl_realness = realness,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_20    = Stabilo_20,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_40    = Stabilo_40,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_1500  = Stabilo_1500,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_3000  = Stabilo_3000,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_error = Stabilo_error,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_mean  = Stabilo_mean,
                Ctrl_Stabilo_med   = Stabilo_med,
                Ctrl_FAB           = FAB,
                Ctrl_Avoid.Attract = Avoid.Attract, 
                Ctrl_Avoid.Neutre  = Avoid.Neutre,
                Ctrl_Appro.Attract = Appro.Attract,
                Ctrl_Appro.Neutre  = Appro.Neutre) -> donne.ctrl


donne %>%
  filter(Bloc != "1") %>%
  left_join(donne.ctrl) %>%
  group_by(Sujet, states) %>%
  mutate(difficulty_delta = difficulty - Ctrl_difficulty,
         emotion_delta = emotion - Ctrl_emotion,
         absorp_delta = absorp - Ctrl_absorp,
         meta_delta = meta - Ctrl_meta,
         realness_delta = realness - Ctrl_realness,
         Stabilo_20_delta   = Stabilo_20 - Ctrl_Stabilo_20,
         Stabilo_40_delta   = Stabilo_40 - Ctrl_Stabilo_40,
         Stabilo_1500_delta = Stabilo_1500 - Ctrl_Stabilo_1500,
         Stabilo_3000_delta = Stabilo_3000 - Ctrl_Stabilo_3000,
         Stabilo_error_delta= Stabilo_error - Ctrl_Stabilo_error,
         Stabilo_mean_delta = Stabilo_mean - Ctrl_Stabilo_mean,
         Stabilo_med_delta  = Stabilo_med - Ctrl_Stabilo_med,
         FAB_delta           = FAB - Ctrl_FAB,
         Avoid.Attract_delta = Avoid.Attract - Ctrl_Avoid.Attract, 
         Avoid.Neutre_delta  = Avoid.Neutre - Ctrl_Avoid.Neutre,
         Appro.Attract_delta = Appro.Attract - Ctrl_Appro.Attract,
         Appro.Neutre_delta  = Appro.Neutre - Ctrl_Appro.Neutre) %>%
  dplyr::select(Sujet, Bloc, age, genre, Hypnos_exp, Medit_exp, states, 
                difficulty_delta, emotion_delta, absorp_delta, meta_delta, realness_delta,
                FFMQ_Total, Harvard_Obj_Total,
                FAB_delta, Avoid.Attract_delta, Avoid.Neutre_delta, Appro.Attract_delta, Appro.Neutre_delta,
                Stabilo_20_delta, Stabilo_40_delta, Stabilo_1500_delta, Stabilo_3000_delta,
                Stabilo_error_delta, Stabilo_mean_delta, Stabilo_med_delta) %>%
  unique() -> donne.delta

Stat

Functions definition

Analysis.AL <- function(var.interest, datas){
  
  # var.interest <- "difficulty_delta"
  # datas <- donne.use
  
  eval(parse(text = paste("datas <- mutate(datas, col.interest = ", var.interest, ")", sep = "")))
  
  datas %>%
    data.frame() %>%
    dplyr::select(Bloc, states, col.interest) %>%
    unique() %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = Bloc, y = col.interest, fill = states)) +
    geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.95) +
    scale_fill_grey() + 
    theme_classic() +
    theme(legend.direction = "vertical",
          legend.box = "horizontal",
          legend.justification = c(0, 1),
          axis.title.x = element_blank(),
          axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
          axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, angle = 0, hjust = 1),
          axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10, angle = 0, hjust = 1)) +
    labs(fill = "States",
         y = var.interest,
         x = "Bloc") -> p1
  
  
  
  datas %>%
    data.frame() %>%
    dplyr::select(Bloc, states, col.interest) %>%
    unique() %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = col.interest, fill = states)) +
    geom_density(alpha = 0.6) +
    scale_fill_grey() + 
    theme_classic() +
    theme(legend.direction = "vertical",
          legend.box = "horizontal",
          legend.justification = c(0, 1),
          axis.title.x = element_blank(),
          axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
          axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, angle = 0, hjust = 1),
          axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10, angle = 0, hjust = 1)) 
  
  model <- lm(col.interest ~ states*Bloc, data = datas)
  anova(model) -> anova.res
  
  
  sjPlot::plot_model(model,
             type = "eff",
             terms = c("Bloc", "states")) +
    ggtitle("Predicted Values") -> p2
  
  emm <- emmeans(model, ~ states*Bloc,
                    type = "response")
  
  test(emm, adjust = "FDR") -> emerg.test
  
  des_cont <- list("Abso_3 VS Abso_2" = c(-1, 0, 1, 0),
                   "Meta_3 VS Meta_2" = c(0, -1, 0, 1),
                   "Abso_2 VS Meta_2" = c(1, -1, 0, 0),
                   "Abso_3 VS Meta_3" = c(0, 0, -1, 1))
  
  contrast(emm, des_cont, adjust = "FDR") -> post.hoc
  
  output = list(p1 = p1,
                p2 = p2,
                emerg.test = emerg.test,
                anova.res = anova.res,
                post.hoc = post.hoc)

}

Run analysis

L’idée était de faire des tests très simplistes pour voir le comportement de toutes les variables étudiées (FAB, Blast et Likert) en fonction de seulement deux paramètres:

  • Bloc, avec 2 niveaux (2 & 3)
  • States, avec 2 niveaux (meta-awarness & Absorption)
  • et leur interaction

Comme notre design n’est pas du tout équilibré, nous utilisons seulement le bloc 2 et 3. Et les mesures sont la différence avec la condition Contrôle (delta).

Pour chaque mesure, nous trouverons:

  • ANOVA resuts:
    Comme son nom l’indique, l’analyse de variance pour voir les effets des 2 facteurs (Bloc et states) et de l’interaction **Bloc*States**.

  • EMERGENCE results:
    Ce sont les tests d’émergence pour tous les blocs et toutes les conditions. Ca nous permet donc de voir si la mesure faite est différente de la condition Contrôle.

  • POST-HOC results:
    Ce sont des contrastes. Entre différents blocs pour un même état. Et aussi entre différents états dans un même bloc.

  • Deux figures:
    La première montre les données brutes et la seconde montre les effets estimés (pour mieux comprendre les tests).

var.to.analys <- c("difficulty_delta", "emotion_delta", "absorp_delta", "meta_delta", "realness_delta", "Stabilo_20_delta", "Stabilo_40_delta", "Stabilo_1500_delta", "Stabilo_3000_delta", "Stabilo_mean_delta", "Stabilo_med_delta", "Stabilo_error_delta", "FAB_delta", "Pheno_Etat_delta", "Pheno_Image_delta") 


lapply(var.to.analys, Analysis.AL, datas  = donne.use) -> output


for (xi in 1:length(var.to.analys)){
  cat('\n\n', var.to.analys[xi], '\n')

  # output <- Analysis.AL(donne.use, xi)
  cat('\n\nANOVA results\n')
  print(as.data.frame(output[[xi]]$anova.res))
    
  cat('\n\nEMERGENCE results\n')
  print(as.data.frame(dplyr::select(output[[xi]]$emerg.test, -SE, -df, -t.ratio)))
  cat('\n\nPOST-HOC results\n')
  print(as.data.frame(dplyr::select(as.data.frame(output[[xi]]$post.hoc), -SE, -df, -t.ratio)))

  suppressWarnings(print(output[[xi]]$p1))
  cat('\n')
  suppressWarnings(print(output[[xi]]$p2))
  
  }
